\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid10496061 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 39, Orient Road, Salford 6.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Marital Status?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Single.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The year of my birth was 1901, and I was born at 245 Chester Road, Hulme, Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me how many years you lived in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me where you moved after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Moved to Pendleton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me why that was? Can you remember the address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, it was 25 Kersle View.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How long were you there, please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now, we were there only 21 months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And then can you tell me where you went to after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 251 Ellis Street, Pendleton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you were there how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Until 1935.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me why you moved in each case?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. Now the first one was a rather interesting one. We were in a little shop, tobacconist and newsagents shop in Hulme and it had been my grandfather's shop, he'd died an
d my father and mother took it. Now, the shop was near to Hulme Barracks and somewhere about this time, I don't just know what year, I should think about 1905 or '06, perhaps, the barracks finished and the men were not there any more and most of the shops
, particularly a tobacconists shop didn't do so well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It depended on their trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. And we ... oh, and about the same time, round about the same time my grandmother had ... she hadn't died, she'd become ill and was in hospital and my grandfathe
r and a younger uncle and aunt came to live with us and we took this bigger house, you see, in Pendleton. It might be interesting to know that I remember the militia walking into Church, marching into Church for Church services.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I
n Hulme; all in their navy blue outfits, you know, it was quite a thing every Sunday morning, from the barracks, you see. Now that's why ... chiefly why we made the move. There were two things, you see, two things together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That was from Hulme to Kersle View?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. Now, we moved from Kersle View because the house in Ellis Street was a more suitable house. I think it had another bedroom. There were 4 bedrooms there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I've no sisters, but I had 3 brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And do you remember the dates of their birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
My eldest brother would be 1899, September 1899, then I came next. My next brother would be born 1903 and my youngest brother was born in 1907.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I think he was 26.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 He came from Hulme, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 At that time, and for most of his life, he was a tallow refiner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That's unusual, isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. That's to do with soap making, and that was his job when I was born. They also had the newsagents shop, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which your mother ran, did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Mother and he ran. Incidentally, the newsagents shop kept open from 6 o'clock in the morning 'till 11 at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What was he after he became a tallow refiner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, he did a bit of traveling, commercial traveling, for a jam firm, I think, but he went back to his original employer, oh, within a very few years, two or 3 years, perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 He worked for a firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 A little firm, a one-man firm at this stage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, that's unusual, isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, they made the tallow for the soap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I see, they didn't do the process of the soap right through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So he was in this job fi
rst, then he went commercial traveling and then he went back to this tallow job. Was he in this 'till he died - the rest of his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, in varying capacities. I mean, he sort of improved in status, shall we say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Went up the scale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Went up the scale a little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And he stayed in that until he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You never remember him being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 He never was out of work. He often said he didn't get very good money, but he kept on getting it (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And he never did any casual or part-time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not for money I don't think, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, she was 2 years younger than Father. I think she'd be 25, or nearly 25.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you know where she came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She came from Pendleton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She was a Salford girl, too. Had she any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She was a weaver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No part-time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No part-time jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't by any chance know what hours she did before she was married, in the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes, they started at 6 o'clock, of course, and I suppose they went on until about half past 5, wouldn't it. She did some half-timing. That school ... I think it must have been 
getting up round about 12 and went one week in the morning to the mill and one week in the afternoon to the mill, and to school nice versa, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I had an uncle did this. This was regular in the mills, wasn't it, in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. She ... th
is was much against her teacher's ideas and I think that for the last year of her school life, or for the last few months of her school life, she went back full time to school. I think she left when she was 13. She must have been very young when she went 
d
oing this half - timing. I remember her saying that - of course, they had to go to work in the dark - and she walked along the canal bank where the mill fire hole, as they call it, you know, the stokers, the boiler, was and she thought it was the devil st
oking the boilers. She was so young that she could have such a ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did she like the work, though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, I don't know, it was very hard work, but she was interested in it. It was hot, of course. One thing it taught her was to lip-read. That's perhaps a point.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I've heard this, yes. Because of the noise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Because of the noise. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 
She said they didn't use their voices, but they held quite long conversations about where they'd been the night before, and so on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And she was very well able to lip-
read. In fact one didn't realise that she was deaf in her old age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She knew all you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 If she was in front of you she knew what you were saying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This happened to weavers, too. All the mill people learnt to lip-read, didn't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, they all could lip-read. They had to learn to lip-read, they couldn't ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't remember where she worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, she worked at the Bridge Mill at Pendleton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I know the Bridge Mill, on Holland Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now I'd like to ask y
ou about life at home when you were a child, the time up to when you left school. How many rooms were there in the house at Ellis Street, would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, I think that's the best place to take. There was what we would call, I suppose, a sitting room, and a dining room and a kitchen and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 a scullery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 , a little scullery, and 4 bedrooms. Four bedrooms and a bathroom. So we came into a bathroom quite early in our lives.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You were lucky to have a bathroom in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. Actually, there was a bathroom at Kersle View, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house? Relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, my grandfather and this uncle and aunt were with us, for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I think not at that stage. She'd had help when we were children in the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, not living in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What type of duty did the help get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, minded the children and washing up and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She looked after you, did she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. Anything that just needed doing ... a bit of cleaning, I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She did look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did she look after you regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, I think she came each morning. It's a bit dim in my memory of this, 
but I know that she took the children out when ... you know, when they were washed and dressed and fed, and so on, and she'd take them out for a walk because ... oh, this was a point: Mother being fast in the shop she had the view that the children didn't
 get out enough, didn't get enough fresh air and old Mummy Holmes, as we used to call her, used to supply that need. She took us out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She wasn't entirely responsible for you, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you think of her? Did you think of her as a servant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, no! No, no. My memory of her is that she was sort of part of the establishment, you know. No, we weren't taught to think of her as a servant, either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And what did you call her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Mummy Holmes, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And what did she call your mother, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I think 'Mrs. Chadwick', I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And she just used to take you out for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She wasn't responsible for your upbringing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, no. Not in any way, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was the washing done at home, or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, it was always done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your mother or father mend the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Mother did. Yes, my mother used to have at least one mending night and sometimes more in times of stress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Even when she was in the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, she always mended the clothes. And my father mended shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, he did the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
He always mended the shoes at home, in those days. He had ... my grandfather had been ... he wasn't actually a cobbler, but he did a bit of spare-time cobbling and he had what they referred to as 'the tackle'.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The last?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
The last and the things to do it with. And I suppose Father learnt how to do it from him, anyway he did do it. And we were always pretty well shod because of that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about the clothes, were they always new, or were they ever second-hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
We were never bought secondhand - or shoes - we never actually wore secondhand things, but if some kind relative had a nice coat or something that would cut down Mothe
r would unpick it and wash it and press it and then start as thought it were new material and make a new garment out of it. But we never wore anything ... I can never recall wearing anybody else's things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember where they were bought, the shoes and the clothes? Were they bought locally, or in big stores?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, they were bought locally. Probably the Co-Op.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You were big Co-Op people, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I don't know about ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That's unusual for shopkeepers, isn't it? They used to be very anti-Co-Op.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Anti-Co-Op, yes. I'm thinking now, perhaps, of the time after I was 8 and then it would be Co-Op.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember when they were bought, the clothes and the shoes, what time of year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, there was always something new for Whit week, and perhaps a new winter coat. And shoes, I suppose, as required.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house? Was he good at cleaning, or cooking, or washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, he helped considerably, but I can't s
ay that work was ever left for him to do, not sort of washing floors, or doing the washing, or anything like that, but this he did if Mother was ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, not at all, no. Didn't mind at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about fires, did he light the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, either he lit them, or later on Grandfather lit them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was always the man who did them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about decorating and repairs, improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Father did most of those. Decorating, always. Yes, I don't r
emember much paying of decorators in those days. There wasn't much money, but father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Although you could get it done quite cheaply in those days, couldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, you probably could, but they would want it doing ... they were rather perfection
ists. If somebody was going to do it cheaply it would perhaps look like a cheap job and that would suit them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So Dad did his own? Now, did he dress, undress or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, he helped. Of course, by the time one was 8 one was doing it oneself,
 but when we were in the shop, that was when we were all under 8, yes, I think it was a co-operative do - he bathed and mother dried and did hair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he read to you and tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, they both did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about taking you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, I don't remember going out a great deal without Mother. When we were ... after we left ... you see, there are two divisions, after we left the shop he and Mother did things together and with us. Before that, if we had to go out
 one would have to go out with either Father or Mother but not both, because the shop was open. Excepting on Sunday afternoons, and then there was a sort of grand parade to Pendleton (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The whole lot of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he look after you when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, of course, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016  to ask}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, we were all given things to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What type of jobs, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, (laughter) I 
remember when we were a bit older, you know, sort of between 8 and school-leaving age - you see, there were 3 older ones - and Mother had a bright idea, I think it was; one cleared the table ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which did this apply to, brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Two b
rothers and a sister, there were only the 3 of us, you see, and we did this in turns. One cleared the table, one washed, one dried, and the one who'd cleared the table put the pots away, so nobody could get out before anybody else, and the one who was goi
ng to put the pots away jolly well saw that it got done quickly. That was the little system she had. Yes, we did that. And then of course, bits of cleaning. And as I got older I was taught how to do my bedroom, cleaning the bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you still carry on after you left school, doing these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes. yes. Yes, I always did my bedroom and I remember ... they were quite firm with us, our parents and Mother would say, once or twice, 'it's time you cleaned your dressing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 table drawers out' and I wou
ld put it off, I'd other things to do and one day I would come home from work and find the contents of the drawer tipped up in the middle of the bed. Well, I'd got to do something about it, or I couldn't go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now, did the older children help the younger children with things they found difficult, like dressing or eating?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
I suppose they did, it was a ... you know, Mother would say 'just put his shoes on' or 'go and find his ...' something else, or you know, something of that sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you look after them in any other ways, apart from helping them dress and wash?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, we'd to take the younger one to school. He was a good bit younger than us and we had to see that he got where he had to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You came at 1903, so 1899 was a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, they were all boys, excepting me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So 1901? So the other 3 were boys, 3 boys and one girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about the younger child, did he help in any way? Did he help you older ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't recall his doing so much for us, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was he your 'fag' or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you expected to go to bed at certain times in your school days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, very firmly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What time, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, it seemed to me always to be r
ound about 7 o'clock, it advanced a little bit for a little ... you know, perhaps half an hour for a year or something like that. The oldest went to bed last, the youngest went first. There was never any argument about it, we just went. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 But I should think 
everybody had gone by about half past 8, until we left school and I can well remember going to night school and night school finished at 9 o'clock - I'd be then 14 or 15 - and I can remember being desperately tired by 9 o'clock, I was so used to being in 
bed a little earlier than that, you see, and of course, later it advanced further than that.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did Mother put you to bed, or someone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, when we were younger Mother put us to bed, I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember at what age you started to put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, she was always hovering round about somewhere at bedtime, there was no sort of going and pleasing yourself and she was always about at bedtime. She was probably seeing to the youngest one and had an eye to the others as well, yo
u see. And one thing about her. I remember when I grew up, of course, and I went to various lectures and so on, hearing a psychologist lecture about not letting children ... not making the place silent for children to go to sleep, and one of Mother's thin
g
s was that we always left what we referred to as 'the middle door' open and life went on the same as normal downstairs and I can remember hearing what they were going. We didn't have lights on, but we didn't have much need for lights, we knew we were stil
l in the family, we could hear and ... she ... very lively, spoke a bit louder so we could hear, and I thought that was a right good piece of psychology. She didn't know she was a psychologist, but she was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, I didn't, I was the only girl. The boys shared a bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you had a bedroom to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Always, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What were the sleeping arrangements of the family as a whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Father and Mother had a bedroom, the boys had anoth
er bedroom, the young auntie had another bedroom and Grandfather and the uncle slept together, whilst they were with us. They weren't there all the ... well, forever. Well, Grandfather stayed 'till he died, but the others didn't. Yes, we'd quite good slee
ping arrangements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What room did you bath in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 In the bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Of course, yes. How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, very often when we were younger, of course. As children I suppose we had a bath every night, less often as we grew older, I supp
ose when necessary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, certainly once a week. Sunday morning was clean clothes day, clean vests, but more than that if we needed them, you see. But not an everyday do, we were expected to keep our clothes reasonably clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Could you tell me where the family had their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, in that house we had a very large living room-kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was at Ellis Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 At Ellis Street, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were there any occasions you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, just occasionally we went into what we referred to as the middle room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Probably referred to as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 dining room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 , now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. It was a badly placed room and ... well, Mother's view was that the meal would be cold by the time you got it there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 In the kitchen and scullery. She had a ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did she have a range or gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She had both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So she used both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She used both.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When was breakfast eaten, what time about? And how many members of the family were present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, if Grandfather was at work, you see, as he was, he went out at 6 o'clock, so I suppose he had his breakfast in the middle of the night, very nearly (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he get it himself, or did Mum help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, he served hims
elf. But Mother was always up to get everybody else off. I dare say she got up at about 7, Father went out at about a quarter to 8; then children's breakfasts, and then all off to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did anyone take out packed meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Father did. And Grandfather did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What type of meals were they, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Sandwiches, usually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did they do about drinking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I suppose they got something where they were? They'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 brew cans}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did you usually have for breakfast, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
We'd have porridge in the winter and strangely enough, we usually had cocoa to drink. It seems a bit odd to me, now, but I think Mother had a sneaking regard that ... feeling that tea was not too good for children, so they had cocoa with lots of milk in.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about Sunday's breakfast, was that different or did you have the same on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't recall it being much different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about dinners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, we always had a cooked dinner. From school we came home to a cooked dinner, which was referred to as a proper dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which was? Do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, meat and potato pie, stew, shepherds pie. And another dish that she used to do was a sort of dish of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 scalloped}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  potatoes with, perhaps, bacon cooked on the top of it, and c
ooked in the oven. The potatoes were sliced, with a few layers ... bit of onion in and bacon on top, or sometimes ribs, you know, put on top. Something that made the potatoes very nice and tasty and we loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And puddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, puddings .
.. we very often had a boiled puddings. Two or 3 times a week we had ... not boiled, steamed pudding. She was very proud of her steamed puddings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Made with suet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, suet. And it would be either raisin, or syrup, or jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Spotted Dog, it was called, wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Those sort of things. And once or twice a week, of course, there'd be a milk pudding, and everybody liked one pudding better than another and the usual theory was 'well, never mind, it will be your turn tomorrow'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about teas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, teas, was mostly bread and homemade jam during the week, lots of, and butter. We didn't have marg. Except in the wartime when we had to. But we had good bread and butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about Sundays, did you have a different type of dinner and tea Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes. Well, there was always a roast on Sundays. Sometimes a roast in the week, but always a roast on Sunday and vegetables, of course. There were always vegetables during the week, too. And very often a steamed pudding on Sunday. And f
or Sunday tea there was always fruit and custard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Tinned fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, only tinned fruit when you couldn't get fruit to stew. Usually stewed fruit. And as we got a bit older, you know, went to Sunday School and went for a walk and if we didn't get i
n by 5 o'clock for this tea we didn't get any fruit and custard, but we didn't often miss! (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about bottling fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, during wartime she did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was the 1918 War?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, she did it even then. She did it even more in the next War, but she did bottle things then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did she make her own pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. But she saw that it was a family do at pickled onion t
ime, everybody sat round a table and if they wanted pickled onions they jolly well had got to peel them (laughter), including Grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So he worked with the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 He worked with the rest, I can see him now. It was always a very joyful occasion, this pickling onion do, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 All crying and laughing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 All crying and laughing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about wine or medicine for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Wine? Oh, they were teetotalers. My parents were teetotalers, as a revulsion from, I think, their pa
rents who were anything but, you see. I think there was an age of temperance society and so on. Actually my father was a
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I was going to ask you about that so perhaps you can tell me about and the Temperance Society, could you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. And ... so there were no wines made, but medicines yes, things like what we used to refer to as brimstone and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 treacle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 . God knows what it was, it was sulphor and black treacle, or something. Spring medicine, I think we called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 For cleansing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes. And then there was some concoction that Father made that we rather liked. It was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 cod-liver}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  oil and honey and lemon juice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you liked it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, he used to put plenty of honey and lemon juice in and he shook it up and emulsified it, you see, he sat the
re hours shaking this stuff, and this was for bad coughs and colds in the winter. Otherwise I don't think we had much medicine, we were fed and kept healthy. We didn't really have a lot of medicine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And they wouldn't brew their own beer if they were teetotal, would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, but this shop that we were in earlier on sold herb beer and ginger beer, which my father did brew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he? For herb beer what type of herb did he use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't know. I suppose this dandelion and burdock and sarsaparilla and all that sort of stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't remember him making it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, I can just remember him making it, and he occasionally made a little after we left the shop, but Grandfather had a way of drinking too much of it (laughter) and he said he wasn't wasting his time!!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Making beer for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 Granddad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Making beer for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 Granddad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  it was herb beer though, it wasn't intoxicant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your father and mother grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, dear me no, we never had a garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they buy any tinned or dried vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, I suppose they'd buy some, but only as a store. You know, they'd have a tin or two of fruit in, I suppose, just for fear somebody called or, you know, somebody wanted tea and there wasn't anything b
y them just at the time, but that was the chief thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they keep any livestock for the family? Hens, pigs, goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, there was enough family. Oh, we had a cat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How many times a week did you eat meat, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I suppose ever
y day. I've no recollection of there ever being a shortage of meat, excepting during the War when, of course, nobody could get sufficient meat. There were lots of meatless days during the War, but not in our childhood.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You'd probably have it how often, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When we were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I suppose excepting the odd day during the week when we had fish we'd have it every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about tinned meat, did you have tinned meat as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't recall there being much tinned meat then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever get some extra meats such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, we didn't know any poachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember seeing your mother have less food so that the family could have more? Or do you remember your father having more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, I don't think Father ever had more, and Mother was a great sharer-out. I think she believed that children needed as much to grow on as father and mothers needed to live on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She didn't have the idea that Father was the breadwinner, or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, but she always saw he got enough food, if it was available.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What if it wasn't available, if it was something special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, they would be short, doubtless.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Father and Mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 They always went short for the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, on the occasions when we would be short, but I can't recall any great shortages of food, excepting during the War.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, we weren't sort of cowed in any way, meals were a social occasion, even when we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You all told your experiences?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 
Yes, not too chattery and not too quarrelly, but not quite as my father used to say about ... in his family, when they were supposed to eat in silence, and he used to refer to a ... I wonder if I can remember it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 A poem that was nailed onto the cupboard door:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 <poem>In silence I must take my seat
\par And give God thanks for what I eat.
\par With knife or fork or napkin ring
\par I must not play, nor must I sing,
\par But for my meat in silence wait
\par 'Til I am asked to hand my plate.
\par Or something like that.</poem>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And it was nailed in the cupboard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
In ... that in my father's day, you see, and if things were getting a bit too hectic when he was Father, you see, he'd quote one of these lines and that's how I come to know it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you allowed to choose what you wanted to eat from the table, or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, we were expected to have what was provided.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have to clean the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 There was no difficulty about that (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What happened if you did leave anything, were your parents cross if by any chance you left something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I think they were reasonable, and I think if we left anything they would know, perhaps, that we weren't fe
eling well, or something. Nobody ever did leave anything (laughter). Mind you, it was always nicely cooked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She was a good cook, your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She was a good cook and you wanted to eat what she cooked. And another thing was that I remember my father saying on one }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 occasion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  that 'if your Mother had stayed in and cooked this, the very least you can do is eat it'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 If there was something on the table, like the salt, could you ask someone to pass it or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, you'd ask someone to pass it, but you didn't grab at things on the table. You said, 'may I have another piece of bread and butter, please', you didn't just grab. And you had your bread and butter before you had your scones, or buns, or cake o
r whatever was ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You had a ration of bread and butter to eat, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Some, anyway. What you were going to eat you'd eat first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, if there was any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you expected to hold you knife and fork in a certain way, and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, not too firmly when we were tiny. The important thing was getting the child to eat its food, but as we grew older we were taught to sit properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How was it? Well, sit up, a
nd hold your knife and fork ... yes, I can remember Mother saying 'don't hold your knife like a pencil', you see. and And the tiny ones always had small knife and fork, so we used to be taught to eat with knives and forks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Where did the little ones sit when they were tiny? Did they have their own chairs and who fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, the one would sit in the high chair, but it would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 be pulled}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  up to the table, they were brought into the circle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And who fed them, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I suppose it would be Mother, or ... whoever was sitting next to the baby, or very likely the baby would feed itself at this stage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you allowed to bring books or toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, dear me, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And when could you leave the table, any particular time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, not quite without permission, but permission wasn't withheld too long. No doubt they were glad to get rid of us. But we had to make some motion about it, you see, 'may I get down'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did the whole family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who was the meal served by? And in what order, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I suppose, Mother, but usually youngest first. I recall it being youngest first. She was rather a
n up-to-date mother for her time, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was your mother and easy person to talk to? Did she show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes. Not a great ... she wasn't very demonstrative, at all. She was reserved, not demonstrative. She said that she showed her affec
tion by what she did for us, not what she said about it. And she didn't care for people, as she said 'mauling each other'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was she an easy person to talk to and could you share worries with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, if there was anything wrong you could tell her, yes, and she usually knew a way out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about your father, was he easy to talk to and could you share worries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, much the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did he show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, to tiny ones, yes, but as we grew older there was a reserve, you see
, which I think was ... I found the same in other people's houses. There was a certain reserve between parents and children that was well kept and it was almost like respect, you know, you'd show them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did they expect you to behave towards them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
They expected us to be truthful, and if there was any punishment meted out there was one, perhaps, for whatever it was you'd done wrong (not that I ever got punished much) and two for telling a lie about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who did the punishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Whoever ha
ppened to be handy. Nobody ever waited until Father came home to do it. One of Mother's ideas was that the punishment should be well related to the crime and should follow quickly (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember a particular occasion when you were punished, and how you felt about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Do you know, I can't remember being punished much, at all. I never was hit. My father never laid a finger on me. I dare say Mother gave me an odd shove, but rather than smacking people she would give them an holy shove ou
t of the way (laughter) She would show her displeasure rather than by doing any beating or hitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You always knew she was upset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you know if you ever resented it at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't think so, no. Might have done at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, with a certain amount of respect. We quarreled, you know, but they had another maxim, too, that I believe they had agreed on themselves when they got married, that they would n
ever go to bed with a quarrel standing. What does it say in the Bible? 'Never let the sun go down upon your wrath'. And it was a very well kept precept, that was, and they taught us that. I don't mean they were forever ramming it down our throats, but a q
uarrel never lasted 'till the next day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not even between children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they say you should hit back, or not, if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't remember, really. I don't suppose they wanted us to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 namby-pambies
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 , you know, but they didn't hold with ... much in the way of fighting, or pushing, or shoving. They did all the pushing that was necessary, they said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be? Did they bring you up to consider certain things
 important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, I think they felt that we should be useful to other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they? The idea of service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, my mother had a great idea of service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You followed this, too, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. I did. My mother had a great i
dea of service, though ... not that she was able to do a terrible lot, but whenever she could do a good turn she would do it and she had very strong views that that should be the end of it. She'd no more ... she wouldn't be telling people what she'd done 
for anybody. If you want to do them a good turn, do it and be satisfied in doing it. Let them tell somebody if they want to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So they always thought you should be of service to someone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me what they considered right and wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, I mean, any thieving, or lying or ... sort of slandering people, talking about people, saying nasty things about them, they wouldn't have it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, now, swearing! Funny, I only spoke yesterday ab
out that. The girl behind here, her washing line broke yesterday and I said then that I remembered one time - I must have been about 13 or 14 - when Mother's washing line broke with lots and lots of clean shirts and all sorts of things, and it didn't brea
k
 into a garden, it broke onto a yard .. back entry, and she swore and I was amazed!! I was absolutely amazed. I'd no idea that she knew the words. I knew that I knew the words, but I didn't think she did. But it really was the very first time that I'd hea
rd her swear. They never swore at us. Oh, no, they wouldn't have any swearing that they heard, anyway. We didn't swear, anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And if grownups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, if it concerned us, yes, but not to interrupt, not to s
o to speak, hold the floor. We weren't quite to be seen and not heard. That was the precept of the previous generation, that children should be seen and not heard. It wasn't quite as bad as that, but we weren't to be rude and interrupt a conversation. But
 
Mother would always turn round after the conversation was finished and say 'now what was it you were going to say to me?'. You see, she didn't let us think that it didn't matter, that what we wanted to say ... many times by that time, of course, we'd forg
otten what we did want to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
When you had a birthday, would it be different from any other day? Did you receive presents, or have anything special to eat, or have guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, we often had a bit of a birthday party. We had cousins, of course, w
ho would come to tea. We had one family of cousins, we had a counterpart in that family. Each one of us had one of them, you see, so very often our joint birthdays were celebrated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, little presents, you know, bits of something or other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 A special party, anything special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, fruit and custard and cake, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember anything you did with your mother and father, together, on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, everything. We played games, and we had ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Indoor games?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes. We had presents, you know. We always had presents, even when we'd forgotten about Father Christmas there was something for everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What type of games do you remember you played normally? Not just Christmas, but ordinarily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, we played games many a time together. We often did ... now, we must talk about Christmas first, mustn't we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, and then we'll go on to the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We would sing, mostly, you know, or have singing games, or have a concert. We'd all do something; say something, do something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Anyone who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, matter of fact, we all sang. We didn't all perform. I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you make music as a group, at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, but singing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No one playing an instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, my youngest brother could play anything, so could my grandfather. They could make music out of a tin whistle, or a banjo, or accordion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have any instruments in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 There were a few odd things, and there was an organ
, I suppose they call it an American organ, you know. A sort of harmonium affair, you know, which we all learnt to play by ear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And this was what you did on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, yes, and many another day, as well. But of course, there was always 
extra food on Christmas Day and bits of decorating had gone on, and such things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about normally, did you play any games with your parents indoors? Or even outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I don't think we did, not outside. But inside, of course, we would play c
ertain games, you know, first and second letter and, you know, things in the room ... guessing games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You gave the first letter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, guessing games. And I'll tell you another game that we used to play. Somebody would strum the time of the music,
 you know, and the first one to get it, perhaps, got a sweet, or something like that, you see. They put in quite a lot of time on those sort of things with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 But they didn't play outdoors with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't think so, only when we went into the p
ark which we quite often did in the summer. We had a ... Bunehill Park was near to where we lived, you see, and ... I mean, Father and Mother would come out with the cricket bats and play games like that with us, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me if you had any books in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, we'd always books, and lots of books. My parents were great readers in different ways. My father read westerns and all sorts of books like that, but Mother read very well. She really was an extremely well read woman and I remem
ber asking her one time how she came to acquire the taste for the kind of literature that she read and she said that her mother, of course, couldn't read but insisted upon being read to, and she said, 'you try reading rubbish aloud'. So she'd always been 
s
elective about her reading and she knew all the classics. She hadn't only read them, she'd read them many a time and often, you know, somebody out of one of the classics would come into her conversation. I remember her saying something about ... one time,
 
about Rosa Dartle. I said 'who in the world's Rosa Dartle?' 'oh', she said, 'one of Thackeray's characters', you see. Well, I've still not got round to Thackeray, I just haven't been able to absorb ... (laughter). But she knew all these characters, she'd 
read all of Thomas Hardy's books and knew them well, knew the characters well, and quoted from them, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And yet she left school as a half-timer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, that's quite something, isn't it. She read right to the end of her days, they both did, 
and - this is perhaps a digression - but it was very good for me when I had the two of them, as old people, here, I could go out and leave them each with a book and they'd be there with the book when I came back, and I'd say to them, 'is this all you've d
one all the evening?' 'Oh, I've looked up and smiled at her every hour!', would say Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they read newspapers, or magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We didn't buy much in the way of magazines. We had one periodical that cam
e every week. I think it was called 'The Weekly Telegraph' and I remember it had a very, very good nature page in it, and my younger brother was very keen on natural history and I'm sure it stemmed from that, reading this particular 'Mr. Out-Of-Doors', or
 
whatever it was called, you know. It was quite a good little periodical, but none of these ... well, there weren't as many glossy magazines and things then. But we'd read anything. I remember once saying to my father, 'you'd read a telephone directory'. H
e'd say, 'well, it's very interesting, you know'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they read out aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 To you as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Always to us, as children, yes. And taught us to read. We could all read by the time we went to school. They 
taught us things as we went along, as we were going upstairs, even as tiny babies, mother would count 'one, two, three' all the way upstairs. She always knew how many stairs were in every house, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You must have been a Godsend to your teachers when you went to school, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't think we were so bad, I think they rather liked us (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you ever remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, my Grandma's funeral. We didn't go to it. No children at funerals. No children in mourning, or anything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember who attended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The family, I suppose, and Grandma's ... my uncles and aunts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was a very modern view of your mother's too, wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 She was for her age quite a modern woman. No, the fi
rst funeral I actually went to was my brother's funeral - or does one come to this later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I will ask you about your brothers, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I was 17 before I went to a funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What year would this be, about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 In 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember anything about the mourning clothes of the early funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, they wore black and if they couldn't get black, they borrowed it (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Always black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, in those days. Not Mother later on, by any means, but in those days, black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes, particularly relations. As I say, we had this family of cousins, there were 10 of them, there were only 4 of us, you see - they carried on after Mother and Father c
eased to produce - and, well, we could immediately have a party, with their 10 and us 4 at whosever's house we were at we had a party, and we could all perform something. We really couldn't get our performances in in time and had to postpone them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who took you when you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Father and Mother. Mother, if not Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about neighbours, did you ever go visiting neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We popped in and out. I popped in and out the neighbours, used to run errands for them and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have friends you visited, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, there were odd friends that we went to see. And, yes, a friend of Mother's. Actually, this lady became a friend of Mother's through my youngest brother and her youngest son. We were going a
way one time and my younger brother particularly wanted this pal to come with him, and the pal wanted to come, too. They weren't having any holidays. And Eric said to my Mother, 'will it be all right? Mrs. Brennan wants to know if Arthur can come with us'
.
 Arthur went to his mother and said 'Mrs. Chadwick said I can go with them if you'll let me'. So the two mothers finally got together, they were only neighbours a street or two away, you know, and they quite realized that this was a put-up job, but it sui
ted them both and Arthur came with us, and came with us for many a year on our holiday after that. And the two mothers became really very great friends and helped each other out in many, many ups and downs in life, sicknesses ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And cleaning and helping, this type of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
All sorts of things, yes. This Mrs. Brennan would come round to us if we were in need and Mother would go round to her, and they did help each other very much indeed. And until the end of their lives they visited each other, p
erhaps not very often, but they always knew what was happening one to the other. And there were one or two other neighbours of that kind, you know. That was a particular instance. But it was these two boys who arranged this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you taken shopping and with whom did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, if we were shopping for clothes we had to go and have our shoes fitted on, or clothes fitted on. Of course, Mother would take us then. And as for ordinary shopping, shopping for provisions and that sort of thing, well we were sent shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
I suppose we did, I can't just recall any particular time, excepting that he taught me to ride a bicycle. Poor man, he ran up and down (laughter) one avenue with me. He was puffed out, but he really did teach me
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, Bank holidays, or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, now in school holidays, there was always a month, you see, we would go to ... perhaps join this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 Brennan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  family or som
e other ... when there are some kinds there could always be some others, you see, and we'd go to Bellevue, perhaps. Or we quite often went to Heaton Park, would take our eats with us, you know, and always once or twice in the summer holidays we were going
 
to Bunehill Park, which was only about 10 minutes' walk from home, but Mother made an occasion of it. There was a tablecloth taken and spread on the grass and the picnic basket - well, the ordinary basket with sandwiches and cakes in it, and you could get
 sort of hot water put in your dry tea, we took a bottle of milk and you could have a picnic in the park and we did do that always, perhaps twice in the school holidays, once in each week that we weren't away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you go away, as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We went away as well, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember how long for? And how regularly you went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We were a bit unusual in that we always had a holiday, every year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which members of the family went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, Mother and Father and the children, and this other bright spark that ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember where you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, we went to Anglesey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Always to Anglesey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Nearly always to Anglesey, and during the War we went once to Hoylake, but it was only because we couldn't go to Anglesey. And we went to
 a village - we went very cheaply and I think the cheapness of it is worth nothing - my father kept the bill from this place the first time we went there, and it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5729048 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 5 for the week for full board for Father, Mother and on this occasion there were 4 children, our four children, you see - young Brennan hadn't tacked himself on by this time - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5729048 
\'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 5 for full board, and ... oh, and cheaper for the children, you know, it was half a crown, I think, a day for the adults and perhaps half of that much for the children.
 But the poor soul hadn't seen the children (laughter)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And the way they could eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
And of course, they had a farm, these people and we were fed like fighting cocks. We went by rail, of course, to Liverpool, then we went by steamer from Liverpool
 to Beaumaris in the Menai Straits, and then ... I remember there were no motor cars in Anglesey at all, I don't think anybody had one at all, but there was a sort of pony and trap affair standing at the end of the pier and Old Mr. Thomas, we got to know 
h
im very well, used to take the family and the luggage - tin trunk, it was - up to Llangoed, which was a couple of miles out of Beaumaris, I think. And I always remember that I felt very special riding in this horse and carriage as I thought it was, until 
we were going up a steep hill and then old Thomas made us all get out (laughter), all excepting Mother, he'd allow her to stay and the horse would carry her up the hill. But I think we nearly had to push the horse up the hill (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What were your activities on holiday in Anglesey, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, we did all sorts of things. Mostly walking, you know, and bathing. We did a lot of swimming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your mother swim in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, Mother didn't swim, but everybody else did. Fa
ther did. Another thing that always sticks in my mind about those holidays, it was always Bank Holiday week, 'cos Father had that week off, you see. And we had to ... somehow or other we'd contrive to save what money we had and we always seemed to set off
 
with a shilling each of our very own we could spend, you see. Of course, when we got there on Saturday night the one and only post office and general store was shut up and on Sunday nothing opened in Wales and on Monday it was Bank Holiday, so it didn't o
p
en then, either and by Tuesday we'd forgotten that money would buy what we wanted and do you know, sometimes we came home with some of that shilling. We were really taught to ... that the best things in life are free. Oh, we walked, we had a wonderful tim
e
. And it's a very funny thing, but only this very weekend, day before yesterday, I went down into Wales - I went to see my cousin - and she had met somebody who knew the daughter of the woman in Anglesey ... the old lady had a daughter ... who was enquiri
ng about our family and would she ask us to write. She'd not heard of us for such a long time. Actually, the last time I wrote to them was when my father died and the very last real outing he had was to their house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days? Saturday and Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, Saturday ... I think the boys used to go to the pictures. The pictures had just started then, but I didn't care much for them. I don't know, I think I went to ... played about, or went to shops ... went 
shopping or something of that sort. I spent me penny. You haven't asked me about me money yet, have you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I'm getting round to that, actually. Did you have different clothes for Saturday or Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 For Sunday, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you spend Sunday, did you play games or did your parents think it was wrong to work on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, we hadn't much time to play games on Sunday. I went to Church on Sunday morning, Sunday School on Sunday afternoon and usually Church on Sunday evening, or if we didn't go in the evening, summer evenings we all went out for a walk, all together.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 As a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 As a family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents attend a place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not as adults, but they'd all been there, and there was nothing you could talk about tha
t happened at the place of worship that they didn't know about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which denomination did you belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Church of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were there any Sunday School outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Always at Whitsuntide, you know, not very far, about half a mile away to some fields, we went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What other social activities organized by the Church did you take part in? Were you in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, they wouldn't let me be in the choir because they didn't have girls in the choir, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were there any other social activities you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The Band of Hope, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you tell me about the Band of Hope? Several people have told me about that, but they weren't sure of what it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, of course, it was a temperance association of some sort, but
 I know that it was run by day school teachers and it was ... usually somebody used to sing, or we played games, or something of that kind. And I think you were supposed to sign the pledge at some part of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever sign it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you know, I 
don't think I did, because my father, although he was very much a teetotaler, much more so than I am now - not that I drink much - he said he didn't think that people should sign their names at something that they were going to do. If they were going to d
o it, they'd do it and if you signed your name you'd feel very guilty, he thought, if ever you ... I don't think he wanted to provide an occasion of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 guilt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  for anybody, you see. And I don't think I did sign the pledge. I don't think any of us did. I must have dodged it because he didn't want me to do it (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So you were in the Band of Hope. Were there any other clubs you were in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I don't think so. Not 'till I was about 14, nearly 14, and then I joined a girls' club choir which wasn't conne
cted with our Church, at all, which was another phase in my life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they have any other activities, apart from the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, they did lots of things. They went in for musical festivals, you know, at Blackpool and Morecambe, and so on. And we 
were always either rehearsing for a festival, or going to one, or talking about the one we'd just been to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was Grace said at meals in the family, and by whom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, we didn't say Grace, but we were taught to be thankful that we'd got some food to eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your father take an interest in politics? Do you remember him talking about it and do you know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 They used to talk ... he 
and me grandfather used to talk about politics. I can remember them discussing the 1911 insurance Act, the Lloyd George Act. What his politics were ... I don't think he had any very firm politics, and having been a shopkeeper he said that he never told an
ybody who he voted for. And he never did tell anybody. He never told me, either, and I don't tell many people, meself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about your mother, was she interested in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not specially, I think. She voted when women got the vote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember your father and mother voting in a general election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, but I don't know who they voted for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And your father voted before 1919, did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, he'd vote whenever he could, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And your mother as soon as the vote came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Now in some places at that time men felt they were losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers, do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No. He was very 
firm that he wouldn't be, as he said, tied by the nose to any party. And he voted for what he wanted to vote for at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was he a member of a political party, or work for a party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Nor your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their leisure time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 They would say they didn't have any. Mother was always mending or sewing. Father would be me
nding the shoes. And they would read. Mostly read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they have any interests outside the home at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not a great deal, only perhaps, pop across to see a neighbour, sometimes, this body I told you about. But not a great deal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did she go out to enjoy herself, and with whom did she go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, she stayed at home to enjoy herself with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When your father got home from work in the evenings, how many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, he didn't often go out, excepting with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 He didn't attend clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your father take any part in sport? Did he attend races, or bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 None of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your father or mother belong to any savings club? A book clubs, a sickness club, or a funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, a funeral club, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was the only insurance, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The only ... a penny a week effort, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I've been hearing about diddlums and knick-knacks, I'd forgotten about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, they 
didn't do anything in the diddlums and knick-knack line, they didn't. They were people who saved up for what they wanted and did without it until they could pay for it, excepting the funeral. (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you get on with your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh,
 pretty well, I think, we had the odd squabbles. I was particularly close to the middle brother, my second brother, the one who was born in 1903.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Any particular reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, we were closer at school. We were both in the school choir, incidentall
y. And we'd similar friends ... you know, his friends were my friends and my friends were his friends, and we did do a great deal together. We went to night school together when we left school. Mind you, he went to a grammar school, I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 As a child who did you play with, brothers or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 My brothers, mostly, neighbours or school friends, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Where did you play? In the yard, garden, street, or homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I should think all of them (laughter). Not garden, we hadn't got a garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What games did you play, do you remember? And were you allowed to get dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, yes, that's ... provided we were reasonable, it didn't matter whether we got dirty or not. We went mostly to the park, you know, and played ball games, I think. But in winter we mostly stayed in in the evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased, or did your parents discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't remember any discouragement. We were taught to be discerning about whom we played with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 For any particular reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Just sort of ... not to catch up any bad habits that anybody else had ... any silly work that other folk were doing. Bit of an eye kept on us. But I don't recall being forbidden to play with anybody, or go with anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you belong to a youth organization?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Nothing, excepting the choir that I joined when I ... just before I was 14.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I should now like to ask you how you spent your free time when you were at school? Did you have any hobbi
es, or keep pets, collect anything, or do gardening? Anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, I don't know. Mostly singing, practicing singing. I was very keen on voice production and singing and that seemed to be mostly what I did, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You didn't go fishing, or for walks? Oh, you did bicycling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. Walks of course, we went walks. We went into the park a great deal during the summer where we'd meet the friends from school, not necessarily the friends who lived in the streets nearby, you see. And then, o
f course, I had this bicycle and went off on that with one or 2 friends who'd also got bicycles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I didn't. I never was able to hit a ball. I didn't find out 'till ... I should think I was well in me fifties th
at I couldn't hit a ball that was coming to me because my eyes are not quite level. Fancy it taking me all that time to find out. That's the reason.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you go to theatres, concerts, music hall? I know you went to cinemas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, the boys went to
 the cinemas, I didn't do a great deal of doing that. Not a great deal, no, I didn't like this Pearl White hanging over a cliff 'till next week. She bothered me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about theatres, or concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now the theatre ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This is while you were still at school, by the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. There was an annual expedition to the theatre by the whole family. Father would go usually to the Theatre Royal for the pantomime or the Gaiety for plays like Alice in Wonderland, Where the Rainbow Ends and those sort o
f things and we were taken to those ... sort of annual treat. Sometimes we'd go to two in the winter, but quite often only to one. It was sixpence in the gallery. I should think the whole show wouldn't cost more than 3/6d. for the family. And I can rememb
er Father coming up from work - he worked nearer to the theatre than we lived - and we had to go and get in the gallery queue ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And Mother, and Mother would pack up some sandwiches, or something, for him and he would buy a pot of c
offee off a man who stood in the street selling hot coffee, up by the side of ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How would he do this, the man in the street, how would he heat it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, God knows what he had under it, I don't know (laughter). I've no idea. But coffee he did sell
, and ... I suppose it would be charcoal. Charcoal it would be, yes. In the little street between the Free Trade Hall and the Theatre Royal. And Father had this mug of coffee and his sandwiches and we had ... we probably saved some of our Saturday penny t
offee and ... well, a good time was had by all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about concerts and music halls, do you remember any of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No music hall, no. And I can remember even then being a bit discerning about it. I'd much rather have Alice in Wonderland, or Where t
he Rainbow Ends, or something that had the story really in it and not the ... sort of music hall type of pantomime, like Jack and The Beanstalk became, you see. I thought I knew the story of Jack and The Beanstalk and this wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, one penny per week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did you spend your money on, apart from in the queue?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, we could either save it or spend it and there were no questions asked. We were given this 
money, we were not allowed to spend more than a penny a week, if we came by any more money from anywhere during the week that was to be put away. That's probably what we went to Llangoed with. But of course, you could, for the penny, get 4 ozs. Of sweets.
 We didn't always buy sweets, the boys would, perhaps, buy caps for a gun, you know, bangers and that sort of thing. I can't remember what I bought, but sweets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Two a penny, boxes of caps, weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. Yes, well, you see, they'd have a ha'orth of sweets and a ha'orth of caps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family? Relations, friends or neighbours? And in what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not at that period, I don't think so. The period I'm talking about is between 190
8 and '17 or '18. I don't recall any help in that period. She had a help later and she had help before, but not then I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 If your mother was ill or confined to bed, how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, the growing family, we were all allotted a ta
sk, and we did the shopping, and she'd teach somebody how to do the cooking, or Father would help with the cooking, at the weekends, certainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about when your younger brother was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, that was when we were in Hulme, he was born then. Well, I think a neighbour came in saw to it then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby and how much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, there were one or two round about. Yes, we saw them ... they'd call, perhaps, you know. Call, perhaps,
 on Sunday for tea, or something of that kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents have friends, and where did you see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, mostly at our home, or their home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they share the same friends, or did your mother have friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, not specially, I think ... I always reckon that they shared friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Your father didn't have any friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, they became her friends, as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were friends ever invited into the home, and how often? And were they offered anything to eat of drink on any particular day or occasion?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, if they came they'd be offered a drink or a bit of supper or something of the kind, if they came in the evening. Usually if they were coming for tea they'd be invited and we'd know they were coming, you see, and there'd be a bit of a spread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 On special occasions would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Special occasions. Yes. And I always reckoned that ... I was never able as a child to differentiate between Mother's and Father's friends, or Mother's friends. As time
 went on I realized that Mother had acquired them first, or Father has acquired them first, but they became mutual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did friends call in casually, or neighbours call in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Occasionally, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, I think so, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
And did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours? Now you said they visited friends; you went to their houses in return, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they tell you about the amusements that they did in those days? They were supposed to have made their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, well, mostly music and games, and there was a great deal of this ... somebody performing or singing something, or somebody telling a tale, or reciting. They'd all sorts of comical recitations, some I recall. 
I remember one time an uncle starting a recitation and Mother saying, so to speak, 'not before the children' (laughter) I've never found out yet what it was!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they ever play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Only sort of sitting around games, you know, Consequences, they used to play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Consequences, what was that like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, you used to write ... everybody had a piece of paper and somebody would say, 'somebody ...' you'd to write somebody's name down, and then you handed the paper round to the next one, 'met ...
' and another name, you see, and where they met, and the paper went round, you see, and all these questions, 'he said so-and-so', 'she said so-and-so', and the whole thing ends 'And the consequence was ...', you see, that's where Consequences came in, and
 then of course, the fun was reading out these strips of paper, because they were all related to each other. And some very funny things came out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Most people divide society into different social classes or groups. In that time before 1918 did you think
 of some people belonging to one and some to another, and could you tell me what the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, of course, there were the work people, and then there were the people who lived in the large houses, for instance the people on Eccles Old 
Road here. It was said at one time that there were ... I think there were 5 M.P.s lived between Pendleton and Eccles, and ... I don't know who they all were, but I knew some of them, you see. I knew the Haywards, for instance, who were ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they live where the grammar school is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The Haywards House in its own grounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
The Haywards House, yes. Now, one of the branches of the Hayward family built the church that I go to, and that how I come to know anything about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which church is this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 St. Anne's, Brindle Heath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they also built Holy Angels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Another member of the family, yes. They came from ... I think, a family of bankers. Mr. Charles Hayward, the one who was sort of our patron, I feel sure that he wa
s a banker, and I ... you know, the ... what had they used to call them? Gentleman bankers, or ... Banks used to often be family concerns, I think. So the Haywards were bankers, I didn't know that. I once went to their house and it had its own chapel, and
 I was very impressed, I remember that. In its own grounds, and the lodge. And then there was the Agnews, who were art people. Still are. You hear of them now in London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were they in Eccles, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, they were at Summer Hill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, where the school is now, Summer Hill School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, the old house, Summer Hill, was their house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 In which class did you think of them as belonging to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, they were definitely the class apart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, the upper class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The moneyed class, pe
rhaps, I suppose. I don't know whether ... how much money they had or what they did with it. But I never was very conscious of being inferior in any way to them. Never at all. I didn't put people into classes very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about the lower classes, w
hat do you think the division was there? That was the upper class you've told me about. What about the middle class, were you conscious of this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't remember consciousness about any middle class. I thought that the ... if there were any lower clas
s than us they were people who drank and gambled and always looked dirty and soiled and very poor. But I must say, it wasn't because they were poor that I thought they were lower classes, it was because of what they did with what they'd got; the drinking,
 the gambling, the swearing and the nastiness. That was the class, to me, not a class as to possessions or money or status or anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 More of less a moral thing you divided them - because of - you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I suppose it was, really. Some of the
m were a bit revolting to me, as a child, you know. Drunks I couldn't bear. And that was my class distinction.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Which class would you think you belonged to, yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, I really belonged to the working class, without any doubt. Father went to work. Still belong to the working class, I think.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And what sort of people belonged to the same class as you would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, people who worked and spent their money properly (laughter). Or what we considered properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, we were brought up to treat everybody with a certain amount of respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Anyone particularly, though, that it stood out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Anyone you called 'sir', or 'master', or 'madam'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I was quite capable of calling the boss 'sir' to the end of me days in my working life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Didn't that worry you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It never worried me in the slightest. I 'sir-ed' a position in life, I think. Didn
't trouble me at all, I never felt in the least inferior by calling anybody 'sir'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever hear your parents referred to in this manner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Only by, perhaps, some of the shopkeepers who wanted to sell them something. I think people would say 'y
es sir' or 'no sir' in a shop now, wouldn't they. Not as much as they used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And the district where you lived, were some people considered more important than others. Who were considered the most important people?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't know. Perhaps the t
eachers, I don't know. I don't know that we were specially taught to regard anybody as being more important than anybody else. They were all important. Perhaps the doctors and the school teachers had a bit more deference than ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you come into contact with them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, teachers, of course, at school. And another thing, we knew the teachers ... they were Church school teachers, we knew them at Church, socially. And of course, the doctor we knew because he was the doctor. We felt he was ra
ther important, I think, yes. I can't remember anybody else very much that I felt any great reverence for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now what about shopkeepers, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 With each other, as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I've no idea who 
they associated with. I knew quite a few of them but they were supposed to associate with their flock and some whom I knew, did. Some didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well of course, as I say, I knew the teachers at Sunday School and so I knew .. I d
id associate with them. And they associated much with each other, and with people whom they'd known over the years. Extremely good teachers, they were. Really very wonderful people, I consider - the teachers of that generation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I didn't know any farmers, excepting the body we went to in Llangoed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember who they associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No idea, at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about employers? Who do you think they associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I imagine with each other. I don't know. Perhaps I was young to know that, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
What sort of people would you say went to Church? A lot of people went to Chapel, can you tell me the difference between Church and Chapel? Probably socially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I never was conscious of a great deal of differen
ce. I always thought the Chapel people were a little bit more prim than we were, a little bit more strict about things. And my mother's aunt and uncle were Chapel-goers and I used to go to their house, sometimes for a bit of a holiday. They only lived at 
W
alkden, by the way, 7 miles away. And they were very strict about not doing this, and that, and some other thing, on Sunday. They wouldn't read a newspaper on Sunday. Least, they wouldn't buy a newspaper on Sunday, they'd read the ... I don't know. Was it
 the Sunday Herald, or something like that? And even in my young mind then, I used to think, 'aren't they silly? It's Monday's newspaper they shouldn't read'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Why Monday's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, because that would employ somebody on Sunday. That was the idea, the
y wouldn't make anybody work on Sunday. They didn't work and they didn't think anybody should work. 'Six days shalt thou labour, do all that thou hast to do, and the seventh ... etc.' and I can always remember thinking at the time 'well, it's Monday's the
y shouldn't read' What they read on Sundays had been printed on Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups, and can you describe a family in each group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, where we lived in this larger house there were some smaller streets adjoining, only a few people who lived in those streets. I don't know that most of them were very much different from what we were. We just had a larger family at that time an
d had a bigger house, but I don't recall any great difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you think the one group felt superior to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I dare say some of them did. We were not taught to feel superior in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were some families thought of as 'rough' and others 'respectable'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And do you think there was a distinction between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, there was some distinction between craftsmen and labourers because craftsmen got a bit more money, didn't they? But not a great d
eal, I don't think. I believe the big difference was the respectable and the not respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, they were sort of forebearing with people who were not, perhaps,
 quite as good as them, but I don't know that they had any sense of inferiority to people who had more than them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class, and why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Only as to being respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was it possible do you think at that time to move from one class to another, and can you remember anyone who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, I think so. The cousins I've told you about, the family of ten that I mentioned before. Now, their father was an engine driver, but as in th
ose days ... he wouldn't have been an engine driver now, he'd have been a university professor. He did teach in evening school at the College of Technology in Manchester, but he taught locomotive ... whatever it is (laugh).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The engineering side of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
The engineering side of it. Now their family all, excepting 3 who became teachers, left school at 14. Three of them became teachers, so they opted for a profession, didn't they. They went to training colleges, or ... yes, training colleges in each ca
se. not to university. A fourth girl became ... she started work in a library, but she got the library diplomas and she's a professional librarian now. A fifth one became a nurse and got pretty near the top of her profession, she was the training midwife 
a
nd supervisor of training nurses for one of the large districts ... for Wythenshawe, in fact. That's her last job, so she went fairly well up in that and she acquired a profession. Now that's 5 of them out of 10 with professions. The youngest son is the d
irector of the firm that he's worked with for some time. Yes, I think that describes a family who's done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you ever remember anyone being described as a 'real gentleman' or a 'real lady' and why do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, it was because of th
eir ... not because of their money. Certainly never because of their money. It would be because of their actions, the way they treated other people and the way they lived their lives. I'm quite sure of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember seeing a policeman round wh
ere you lived as a child, and what did you think of him? When you were naughty did your mother ever say 'I'll call a policeman'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Mother never said she'd call anybody if anybody was naughty. She dealt with it. But she herself ... now it was very funny.
 When we grew older I had several friends who were policemen, members of the ... young fellow whom I knew ... whom I'd known and they became policemen and my mother didn't quite like it. They were quite nice lads, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Why, do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, she said that she never even liked to be seen talking to a policeman (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I wonder why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't know why, but she'd got a bit of a thing about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How do you think they treated the people, though, when you were a child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The policemen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, he appeared and the miscreants disappeared! (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So he was treated with very great respect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. He'd only to loom up in the distance. Or the sarge'd be tapping his stick on the ground and these activiti
es ceased with the little lads, and so on. How anybody grownup felt towards him I really don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't remember what you thought of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I never thought about him at all. I wasn't frightened of him in any way. I knew one or two men who we
re policemen who belonged to the church that I went to, actually. Oh, they were all right, they were quite matey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, until I bought this one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever see anything of the landlord and how did you feel about him, as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
I didn't have any feelings about him. Anyway, it was an agent, it wasn't the landlord. I had no ... he got his rent every week ... and I don't know that I had any special feeling about him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, well, they did. We were kept quite conscious of the fact that it was only by skill that the money was made to go as far as it did go, you see. And it was, too. We weren't allowed to think that they money grew on 
trees, or anything, you know. I remember a girl saying to me one time during the week, we wanted to do something or other, and she said 'go and ask your mother for a penny' and I took a deep breath and I thought 'Oh!! Ask Mother for a penny!!??' I wouldn'
t }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 dream}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  of going and asking her, and of course she would have said no, I knew that, but I wouldn't have even asked!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did you think about your parents having to struggle for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I don't know that I had any deep feelings about it. I 
thought that when I grew up they wouldn't have to struggle quite as hard. But I had a feeling that the struggle was temporary, that we should grow up and we should make it easier for them, which I think we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill? You said he was never out of work, didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, he was never out of work, and even if he was ill he was never short of his wages. He wasn't ill very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever have to get help from anyone, the parish or anyone like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
No, we didn't, but that's a point. I do remember on one occasion Mother having to go to the Relieving Officer, not to get relief - she went for something else - and the Relieving Officer in those days was a very autocratic bod, you se
e, he was used to giving out largesse, and she was coming out ... she hadn't asked her to sit down which she didn't approve of at all, and as she was coming out he said 'and shut the door behind you', so she kicked it open with her foot. And that is the s
ort of person she was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were you ever given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor, or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, no, I just went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I understand that I was 3, and I went on my own (laughter
). It was a little school round the corner from where we lived. My older brother had gone to school, and I went after him and stayed. I think Mother went after me and the teacher said 'oh, let her stay, it'll be all right'. And I believe I started school 
when I was 3.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What time did you go when you started properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And what time did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I think the infants came out at 4, and half past 4 for the seniors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What kind of school was it, a private school, a Church school ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was a little Church school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was it mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This little school was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you get to school? How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, about 3 minutes, round the corner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who went with you, anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't think so. Probably me elder brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 At home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did you think of school, did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I always liked school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I liked them, too. I think they rather liked me (laughter).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you think that the teachers emphasised certain things as important in life? Manners, tidiness, punctuality, ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, yes. Punctuality, of course, was a great thing. I don't know that they succeeded ve
ry greatly in that with me, but I always remember it as something that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
 necessary. Mind you, I didn't be late at school. I wasn't late as school. I think only on one occasion was I late and it was when I was much older, I must have been about 13 an
d I'd gone to see a wedding. One of the girls at school was being a bridesmaid for her sister. And I wouldn't have been late that time, but I went in the boys' entrance at Holton Bank which was ... which you could get in through the boys' entrance and I w
ould have been in time, only somebody caught me and sent me round. Otherwise I never would have been late for school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about manners and tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, they did emphasise good manners and tidiness, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, I suppose we were taught not to speak in a slovenly manner. We were at home, too, if it came to that, we were not allowed to clip our words, you know, and be slangy. Not at home any more than at school. We might have had another language outside,
 that was ... most children are bilingual (laughter) and ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen? How did they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I suppose they ... I can remember odd people getting the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Girls as well as boys, do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember some of the offences it was for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
No, I don't really. Must have been a heinous crime, because I don't think it happened very often. Though I do recall one teacher - and I saw her the other day, 
too - giving me a slap with a ruler ... the only time anybody ever did cane me ... and it was because I didn't join the loop of a letter on the line, and she smacked me for it. She hit me for that. It must have been a bad day for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did your parents show an interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they ask what you did at school, or visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, yes. Yes, there was nearly always one or more of the teachers knew them. Knew mother, Anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So your parents met the teachers, did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And did the children in school come from similar types of home as you, or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. As I grew older ... At this little school, of course, there were ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was the little school in Hulme, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The school 
in Hulme, the little school, we were rather better than most of the children who went there. A small incident there; the teacher told my mother this after. When I was a very little girl she'd asked which child in the school - it was a dirty little school 
-
 which child hadn't had a wash that morning, you see, and I was the only one who stood up. Well, this struck the teacher as being a bit strange and she came round and - she didn't come to see Mother about that, she knew her, you see - and she was laughing
 
about it. And Mother said, 'oh, well, that would be because she had a bath last night and so she had just a wipe round her face this morning, she wouldn't count that as a wash', you see. But that was it, you see, all the other children must have been asha
med of not having a wash.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you remember \{BLANK\} this school, this one in Hulme?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Only the infants school? And you always went home from here, this was the one you went home from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I always went home, always from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 At what age did you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 leave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I would be about 7 or 8. It was either 1908 or 19-- ... I think it was the end of 1907.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And then you went on to Holton Bank after this, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I went to St. Anne's Church School, first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was in Brindle Heath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 In Brindle Heath; and then to Holton Bank which I really did at the time ... at 11, at the time that people nowadays would take their 11+.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You moved up to Holton Bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We moved up to Holton Bank because we lived rather f
ar away. You see, when we lived in Kersle View for 12 months we went to Brindle Heath school which was near to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you find the Church school, Brindle Heath School, for discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, it was a very good school. And of course, all the teachers there knew my mother, they'd taught her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were they very strict on discipline? Did they punish you much at the Church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not much punishment. I mean, I consider discipline and punishment don't really go together. I don't regard discipline 
as how much or how little you're punished. I mean, if the discipline is good there ain't any punishment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't remember them punishing any children, though? Or what method they used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't recall ... Oh, well, there was a strap kept in the 
headmistress's drawer, but I don't remember ever seeing her use it. But it was a strict school. I mean, we were ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you like the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes. Yes. I knew some of them 'till they died. I were great friends with them. At Sunday School, of course, as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You would get the same Sunday School teachers as at the day school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 There, yes. Now, at 11 I went to this new school, Holton Bank ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was new then, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was new either nineteen hundred and ... I should 
think it was 1911, I think we went the first year it opened, chiefly because by this time we lived father away from the church school and had to cross two main roads which were getting busier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And did you go home for your dinner at Holton Bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, we always went home for dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who took you when you were at Holton Bank, then, if you crossed a main road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, nobody took us by 11. We were taught to cross roads. And Holton Bank School was rather superior, we learnt a few things there ... 
for instance, we learnt French there. Yes, we learnt French, and all 3 of us, the older ones, we learnt French there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was in 1911, you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 We nearly taught my mother French by the time we'd finished. We would say French phrases at the table you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was it a mixed ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, it wasn't mixed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I mean mixed as regards background in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Rather the better, I think, went there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was in a good district, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was in a good district and people seemed
 to come from other districts to it because it was a good school. Well, from the Heights, and I know one man now who came from Swinton. Don't know quite how he got there from Swinton, but he did because it was a good school, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were there any gangs or groups in the school? Now let's start with the infants' school. Would you remember this in the infants' school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I doubt that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about St. Anne's, did you have groups or gangs in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, different people would play togethe
r. But of course, gangs didn't quite apply to girls like it did to boys. I think there was a bit of ganging up with the boys, but I don't remember anything much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 St. Anne's wasn't mixed? Was it separate boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, separate boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And Holton Bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That was separate boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What about Holton Bank, do you remember gangs or groups in that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I can't remember much. There were people who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 belonged}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  to certain things, for instance they took a 
great interest in art there. That never included me at all. And also they had a school choir which did a lot of rehearsing practically all the year round. Well, that did interest me tremendously. We used to stay after school for choir practices, you know,
 
not just in school time. Well, the groups of friends that you had were either in the choir, or painting frescoes round the walls, or ... I think there was a little tennis club there, too, but that, of course, ... I never could hit the ball, so I never joi
ned that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
In either St. Anne's, or Holton Bank, do you remember any children being left out of things and did teachers in either school single out certain children for different treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not that I remember, no. I was never conscious of that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you don't remember the teachers singling them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
No, I can't, no. I think that ... you know, brighter kids were ... perhaps pleased the teachers more, but I don't recall anything nasty, in any way, going on. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 14.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I don't know. I suppose I had the opportunity. Various girls went in for the scholarship during their 13}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  year, then and of course, really, the girls wh
o then went to what was called the secondary school, which would be the grammar school now, they were usually going in for a profession. They were mostly going to be teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And yet you finished up an almoner, which is ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, but years and yea
rs after that. I had to do a lot of learning before I did that. I think the idea at home was that by this time, you see, we were growing up, we were taking rather more money than there was available and I think Mother didn't want us to be - my older broth
e
r had left school at 14 and so did I, and I think she didn't want us to be sort of the poor ones on the next rung of the ladder. Shall we say, she'd like us to be a larger fish in a smaller pond, you see. Now by the time my next brother came, he did go to
 
the grammar school and he did very well there, too. I suppose if it had been the usual thing to do I would have gone on, I would have got the scholarship all right, I think, because at the end of the ordinary school term I came higher in class than all th
e girls who'd got the scholarships.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you go on to any evening education afterwards, or part time education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes. Yes. Now that we all 3 did very thoroughly. I went 3 nights a week to night school, both summer and winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What were the subjects?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
In the first instance the subjects were business ... shorthand, typing, bookkeeping and English, I think. Yes. And then, by the time I was, I think, about 17, I had by that time started work at the Health Office, and one of the conditions of
 service there was that you took the Sanitary Inspector's exam, which was the only exam that were was in those days. And of course, the whole thing was designed for boys; this girl got into it (laughter) just because of the war, you see, they had to take 
girls on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You broke in. Did you chain yourself to the railings, or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
No. And I went to the classes at the Tech, also 3 nights a week, and Saturday afternoons, too, we had to go. Now, I didn't take the Sanitary Inspector's exam because by 
the time I could take it at 21 the war was over and there weren't going to be any more lady sanitary inspectors, they didn't need them, you see, but that didn't alter the fact that I had all the training, you see, and I did that then. And simultaneously w
i
th that I was in this Salford Girls' Club Choir, which was really a recreative evening class. So that's four nights a week I was out, and there wasn't much time to do anything wrong, and I thoroughly enjoyed it all, particularly going to the Tech night sc
hool, you see, and I remember on one occasion, one period I was in a class with ... there were 30 in the class, 29 young plumbers and me!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you resent this, when they discarded you, more or less after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, no. Well, by that time I'd sort of got well tucked in to another line of country. No, it didn't trouble me at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You mentioned, before when we were chatting, that you went to university, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I went to several courses at the University. That was later than that, and fo
r special things that I was going to need in the job, you see. For Social History ... I think I did two winters at that and a couple of winters at Psychology, and innumerable courses that I'd been to on special things, you see. So perhaps all added up tog
ether it would amount to a university course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
No, I don't. No. And I think sometimes that the folk nowadays would be better employed having 'in service' training. Being trained, having their knowledge widened whilst they were doing some job. I think there'd be less troubles about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 When you were at school did you have a part time job, or any means of earning a little money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, n
o. A few errands for a neighbour that you got the odd penny for, you know, but I must say we weren't very encouraged to take money for doing services. That was one of the ways we were taught to be of service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now you've already told me that you went to work at the Health at your first full-time job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No. Not the very first. I was at Kendall Milne's as a clerk for 5 months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who got you the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 There was at that time a Juvenile Employment Bureau in Salford with 2 very good people in charge
 of it, and - of course, my mother went there with me in the first place - and I got this job at Kendall's, you see. But we'd already said ... I think my mother had already said, that she'd wondered about a job in the ... you know, to do with health servi
ce in some way, or that kind of work. She must have thought that that would be the right work for me, I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What hours did you work at Kendall's, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, that was 9 till 6, I think, and Saturday mornings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Saturday mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, everybody worked Saturdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Of course, because it was a store, wasn't it. Do you remember if you had holidays with pay at Kendall's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I can't remember, I don't know. Anyway, the pay was only 5/-. But incidentally, they gave me a shill
ing rise, the boss gave me a shilling rise and swore me to secrecy. So when I left, after 5 months' service, I was getting six shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, it was what other people were getting, you know. I went to the Health Office for 8/-, so that was really a step up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you felt that was a fair wage, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you give any of the money to your mother, and do you remember what it was spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I gave it all to me mother, and it was just spent on me, I suppose, went in the family coffers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you get on with the other people you worked with, and how did your employer treat you at Kendall's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I was always treated well and I've always enjoyed being at work and, I think, enjoyed most of the people I worked with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You liked your employer, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. Well, I don't know what you'd call a Corporation as an employer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was in the Health Service. How about Kendall's, did you have an individual ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, he was a dear. He was a very nice man. He was the man who gave me the shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did you feel about your work at Kendall's, did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I didn't dislike it, I just thought it was what I had to do. There were parts that you like better t
han other parts, you know, particularly going round the shop and seeing various ... I think one of the jobs was to ... it was an order department or something that I was in and you'd to take the order to the buyer in the various departments, you see, and 
so I got to know all the buyers in a very short time, and I rather enjoyed toddling round this shop. And I can really remember seeing Mr. Kendall and Mr. Milne. There was a Mr. Kendall and Mr. Milne. I remember them in the shop, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You don't remember what type of people they were, or how they treated their employees?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, very quiet people, you know, very remote from the underlings like me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now, can we go on to the Health. How did you like this work when you went to the Health Offices?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I enjoyed it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did it alter your attitude to school when you went to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I don't think so, I still went to school, didn't I, in the evenings. No, I liked school, and I enjoyed going to work, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You were at the Health all the time, all your life, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Do you think you'd ever have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, I don't think so. I don't think so, you see, I grew with the job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have a training period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, excepting this Sanitary Ins
pector's course which I took, which was all about public health work, it wasn't just doing drains. It included chemistry, sanitary law - you know, I knew when all the Acts were passed, and what they referred to - and all the various facets of the Health D
epartment, not only the one I was working in, and I quite enjoyed going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you belong to any trade union, or any professional organization? And did you take part in any of its activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 A member of NALGO.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 National Association of Local Government Officers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did they do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did they do? Well, I don't know. They fought for more money but they had a very tough fight, we didn't get so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have any activities, apart from the odd fight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, 
the odd dance now and again, you know. Oh, yes, I quite enjoyed that part of it. There were quite a few odd things we did; the odd picnic we went on now and again, with NALGO, and one or two visits to places I believe I went round Strangeways with them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Strangeways Prison?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes. And various things like that. There's just one little point about that, nothing to do with this period but it's perhaps worth saying. Not many years before I left Salford became a closed shop and we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 to belong to a union
 or a professional organization. Well, by this time I belonged to a professional organization as well as the NALGO, which was regarded as the union, and I hated being made to do things, so I came out of the NALGO.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And you stayed in the professional ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Me little tiny blow for freedom (laughter). I was very annoyed about it. Of course, I had to arrange that all the people who were employed in the department that I then ran ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Tell me about your job at the Health, you started as a ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I started as a clerk. Yes, and I was in the Sanitary Inspectors Department first, as a clerk, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This would be what year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 1915 I started work. And then gradually by about ... I seemed to work in all the departments, as a clerk, you kn
ow. And then coming up to 1917 there was a Child Welfare Department, which incidentally, Salford had started }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
 the 1918 Child Welfare Act. We'd got an established ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What did it consist of, the Child Welfare Department? What were its activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Running clinics, and the health visiting service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 They're noted for this in Salford, aren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, they were. They were pioneers, of course. And I took part in the pioneering and knew the pioneers. I knew the first Health Visitors that
 Salford Corporation ever employed. And it's perhaps worthy of note that even before the Corporation employed Health Visitors there were Health Visitors employed by the Ladies' Public Health Society, a voluntary ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That was unusual, a Ladies Public Health Society, was it? How was it run?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, it was a collection of ladies who saw a need and employed somebody to go round and teach women how to care for the children, you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And it was supported by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Voluntary contribution, of course, by the ... people like Mrs. Hayward and various other ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they actually take part in it, the ladies, or did they just supervise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, they did some of it. No, they did some of it, they ran clinics. They ran one or two clinics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The Haywards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Not Haywards, particularly, but members of the ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 That class of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, that class of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were the clinics well attended in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I'll say they were! Yes, because the mothers could bring their children to the cli
nics and didn't have to pay their doctor. That's why they came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 They dealt with what? Minor ailments, or general ailments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, minor ailments and detected not minor ailments and referred them to hospitals, doctors, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What would happen at the clinics, would you have a doctor in attendance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, and a nurse, and a little clerk, you see, to see that everyone went in order, and kept order in various ways, marked the cards when the babies had been weighed, and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You'd see a lot of poverty in Salford, wouldn't you, at these clinics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, a great deal of poverty then. A great deal of poverty. And then I kept on doing that, and things like it until I was in my late twenties. By this time there were 5 or 6 clerks in the Ch
ild Welfare Department, and the senior clerk left and I got her job, so I became the Chief Clerk in Child Welfare then. And there I remained until 1943 when they seemed to want an almoner to do some work in connection with tuberculosis, which really was a
 
little bit of the Beveridge Plan put into operation before the proper scheme came in 1948, you see. And I did that. And then I did a period of being an almoner in the V.D. department. This, of course, is coming up to the next war. Well, from 1943 to about
 1947 or '8, I think, I took on various bits of social work in the Health Department - I'm sure anything that nobody else was handy to do they gave to me - and started various services, and ended by organizing the Home Help Service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And that's a good one in Salford, too, isn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was (laughter)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Going back to 1917, what about this pioneer health visiting? You took part in that, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I didn't do that, health visiting, I was a clerk. But I knew the people, you see. The Corporation
 took on some of these people who'd been employed by a voluntary organization. I think it was in 1913 that the Corporation took them on, and there were 7 health visitors when I first started. Of course, I knew all of them; knew them well, and good women t
hey were, too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest among workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I don't know that I quite understand that question ... division of interests.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests? This, again would be difficult in the Health.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
It would be difficult. We were all going to the same end, we were all public servants and we all had the same aims, so if there was a great deal of difference, I didn't notice it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Some people say that in those day
s there was a great deal of division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, but in the Health Office were was a great deal of difference between professional people and non-professional people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Greater than today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, no, it's always lasted. No, I think it's greater today, I think it's built up and it's a great pity because one side of a team can't work without the other. Always a great sort of sneer, almost, in the word administration and clerk - 'she's ju
st a clerk', you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This applied mostly when you were young, did it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
It applied right to the end of my time. And some of the clerks that I had in my department at the end, and I myself, we were all social workers by that time, and there were e
xcellent women ... excellent women - two of them are still there running the department now - and the fact that they hadn't had professional training ... they had had training in the job that they're doing and, of course, they're older women, they've got 
a
 wide knowledge of other facets of the job, you see, and of life in general, and they're doing very, very well, indeed. And of course, with all this they are - as I hope I was, also - a good clerk. And you'll find very often that when something flounders,
 when some service flounders in various ways, it's always because they haven't got a good clerk. If they had it'd never be let to flounder, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way? Going to the Health
 Office, did it change your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
I remember thinking when I went to the Health Office 'well, I'm coming here from serving the very rich - as were the people who went to Kendall's - to serving the very poor, which were the clien
ts at the Health Office at that time. I liked the Health Office better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You preferred to serve the poor, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. They'd more need of you. More need. Anything that you would do, everything that you knew how to do and a lot more besides, you 
could have given if you'd had it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 There was great poverty in Salford, wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, there was then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You saw a lot of it, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, some very, very ... some poverty that needn't have been, but a great deal of poverty that couldn't have been helped.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How do you mean, that needn't have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, in that they didn't use the money that they had wisely. Perhaps they hadn't the brains to use it wisely, in which case they were to be pitied rather than blamed. In some cases th
e money could have been better spent, but they would have needed to be very, very clever, I think, in some cases, too, to make the money go round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Now I'd like to ask you about your life at home after you left school. Did you continue to live at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents, at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Oh, not more than any other adolescent. You immediately begin to think that you know more than your parents at 14, who doesn't. And you gradual
ly treat them as though they are the people to be taught. That always happens, but you get straightened out if you've got understanding parents who know how to deal with such things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 And what about your brothers, did it alter your attitude to your brothers when you were working?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, I was as good as the next, you know, I had a bit to do to keep up with my brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you spend Sunday any differently now? Did you still go to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 I still continued, my brothers didn't so much. But I 
did continue this interest at Church and became the Sunday School Superintendent, eventually. And learnt a great deal from there as to how to understand people. You see, so often you'd get somebody in the office and you'd really need to understand them ri
ght away, it was no use making up your mind next week what sort of people they are. Somehow or another they'd got to be understood immediately and they'd got to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 feel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016  understood. Sometimes you can make them feel understood without really understanding them. 
But to do anybody any good, in my way of thinking they've got to feel that you understand them, and that is something that you learn over the years at ... I don't know anybody who can teach it. And I learnt that as much at Sunday School and dealing with c
hildren as anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you take an interest in politics in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No, because, working for a Council, politics changed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How do you mean, it changed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, sometimes it was ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, and you had to be allied to the ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You had to do the job whoever was politically in the Council, you see. And my job was to put the policy into practice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Even if you disagreed or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Whether you disagreed or not. I disagreed sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You never took any part in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 No. I didn't feel that it was the right thing to do, because you would be ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever resent the policies that they put in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, occasionally, yes. On both sides (laughter). Yes, one did resent them occasionally, but it wasn't a good
 thing to be tied to one and hating the other, you'd got to live with both, or either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Tell me something. Did you notice a difference ... you would come into contact with this ... if you can remember back when you first started at the Health, can you remember a different type of person being in politics then in the Council?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, much more the gentry, or the good business people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were in local politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Were in local politics then. They gradually became more working people. Some 
extremely good people, very, very good people who I sometimes thought had the politics instead of the Christianity, but it was the same thing. But there were others, of course, who were in politics to be heard, who were performers rather than doers of goo
d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 What, the people before 1918 when you first started at the Health, they would be the gentry, do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 The same thing may have applied to them. I didn't know them separately as well. But I know, you know, the positions that they held, they
 would be ... a few of the local doctors were in; one or two solicitors and such like people, and people in a good way of business, and so on. But they gradually went ... find you, there are such like people on, now, but not quite the same sort of people,
 though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
You told me earlier that you liked to spend your spare time on music. Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way, or did you do things differently after you went to full time work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, well, we continued with this choir. I 
continued to belong to that practically ... well, until the choir leader died. Not there's just a point about that. The lady who were in charge of this choir was one of the upper class, sort of thing. She was of the Eccles Old Road type. She didn't live t
here, but ... she lived in Sale, or somewhere. And she professed herself to be a socialist, and I used to say that she was the only socialist I knew who had something to give instead of something to get. I don't know that that's quite true now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 This was your memory of your adolescence, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Well, yes, up to about 18, 19, or something. And she didn't feel ... she needn't have worked at all, you see, but she didn't feel that she should go on living on money that her father had made, you see, and t
hat she should do something to earn her living so that she could say that she could earn a living. Well, she was a very well trained musician, she'd been finished in Germany, you know, and all the rest of it. She was a marvelous musician. And she had this
 
choir at Salford Girls' Club; the also had another choir at Ancoats Girls' Club, and there was a sort of bit of healthy competition between us. There was a very large concert in the Free Trade Hall once a year, and many small concerts in between given at 
various places - these competitions that we went in for, all of which had to be rehearsed for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
 meticulously and really, it was an excellent choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Was this before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes. And it went on, of course, during the war - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 incidentally}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 , she was a p
acifist, too - and she was a member of the Women's International League, and in 1921 there was a sort of congress or some such thing in Salzburg of the Women's International League, and there she took the choir, so we went on a fortnight's holiday there, 
y
ou see. And we sang in marvelous places. But of course, we rehearsed for this twice a week and most Saturday afternoons for nearly a year. We were an almost perfect choir by the time we got there. It was wonderful. And this choir ... it was supposed to be
 
a working girls' choir. We did all work, but we worked in various ways. Some were mill girls, one was a bank clerk, one was a teacher, one was a local government officer (me), one or two library ... but we did a variety of jobs and of course, we had a ver
y
, very enjoyable time. We all loved singing and music, you see. And she was a person who wouldn't have us made to feel inferior in any way. Wherever she took us - she took us into the best hotels, she paid for most of it. I tell you how she paid for it. S
h
e put her salary into what she called 'The Choir Fund', the salary that she got for these two evening classes, into the Choir Fund. And I remember when we went to Salzburg, girls who had been in the choir so many years had so many pounds taken off, you se
e, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5729048 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 1 a year off the costs. I know it cost me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5729048 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 12 for a fortnight and I wasn't by any means the one who went cheapest, I should think, perhaps one of the dearer ones, you see. But she always took us into the best places. She taught us how to behave. Any o
ne of use could have gone in any hotel anywhere in the world by the time she'd finished with us. And held our heads up quite high, we were perfectly all right anywhere. And wherever she took us, even if it was to somewhere like Blackpool or }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794496\charrsid1122016 Llandudno}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 , or somewhere like that, it would be into the best caf\'e9
 that we would go not the little hole in corner places where she could be ashamed of us. And she never needed to be ashamed of us, she took good care of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 So she was quite valuable in your training?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, very valuable, to quite a large group of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 How did the mill girls in the choir get on with the professional types?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Perfectly all right. We loved 'em all. We were all great friends, great friends. In fact, some of us are friends yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever do anything different, apart from this? Did you go out in the evenings? Anything different to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Well, I went ... later I went to dances, you know, perhaps dances at the Church, and that sort of thing. But I was never al
lowed to be out very late, you know, not 'till ... well, not 'till after the war, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Who did you go to the dances with? Did you make new friends, boys and girls at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Boys and girls at Church, you know. Boys and girls went to Church longer then than they do, now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Is that where you met then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes, mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you ever bring friends home? Were you allowed to bring them home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, yes, of course, we always brought them home. We were expected to bring them home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 It was a policy of your parents'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did you have any special friends at that time, boys or girls, and where would you go with them, before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Oh, you always had a sort of lad in tow, you know (laughter), and special girlfriends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Your parents did meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Did they expect to know where you were when you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 
Yes, perhaps not in so many words, but you didn't really go anywhere without telling them. I do recall onetime during the 1914 to '18 war, th
e boy that I was quite keen on writing to, he came home on leave. And he ... he had worked at the office, and we went out to tea and to the pictures in Manchester, you see. Well, this was a night school night and I wasn't supposed to be anywhere but night
 school - it's one of the few times that I ever practiced any deception - and there wasn't much wrong, you know, we were home for ... in fact, we were passing the Tech just as they were coming ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 You had to be home at a certain time, did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10496061 K  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9175419\charrsid1122016 Ye
s. I was home at the right time. And just on the Monday evening when I was going out to night school my mother said very quietly, 'yes, and mind you go to night school to-night. Don't let me hear of you being up Oxford Road with a soldier'.
